SHA is a hashing algorithm. It hashes the diff of your commit
Which gives you a unique Id for the commit
So when you see GitHub.com/myname/reponame/commit/123-123-1234 That last part is the commit id, or SHA

UniBridge BOT 29-Jun-17 11:50 PM
<Perry> normalizing is just setting the length to 1
<Perry> has nothing to do with accuracy
<Perry> the thing is you want the length of your velocity vector to be the speed of the projectile
<Perry> but you want the direction to stay the same
<Perry> so you do this by normalizing your direction vector (settings its length to 1 in the direction of your target)
<Perry> and then you multiply by your speed (1 * speed) = speed
<Perry> if you didnt normalize the speed of your projectile would depend on the distance to the target
<Perry> which you don't want ofcourse
<Perry> unless you do
<justnaighty> yeah my thought process for normalizing was if any value of x y z > 1 set it to 1 rather than length to 1
<Perry> yeah that would be funky and not really useful
